} else {
    System.out.println(&quot;the greatest number is &quot; + b);
}
```

Your list of conditions would be more clearly written as:

- if (a&gt;b) : a is greater than b
- *Otherwise*, if(a==b) : both are equal
- *Otherwise*, b is greater than a

That makes it clear that you actually need an &quot;else if&quot; in the middle:

```java
if (a &gt; b) {
    System.out.println(&quot;the greatest number is &quot; + a);
} else if (a == b) {
    System.out.println(&quot;both are equal numbers&quot;);
} else {
    System.out.println(&quot;the greatest number is &quot; + b);
}
```

At this point, the three branches are tightly linked to each other - you can&#39;t put that extra statement before &quot;else if&quot; (but outside the first &quot;if&quot; block) because the &quot;else if&quot; is joined to the first &quot;if&quot;.

